<title>|u&apos; ||ke&apos; in food</title>
<summary>The man who is cleansing himself (performing a purification ritual, or |koa) puts some |u&apos; ||ke (from the |u&apos; ||ke&apos; plant) into the |kui food he has cooked on the fire. He scrapes a little into the food. After eating it he lies down. The |u&apos; ||ke&apos; plant intoxicates people.</summary><comments>1) See also <i>The |u&apos; ||ke&apos; or Tshaka</i>, 2) 9920v: !nanni heard this from his paternal grandfather (Karu), 2) This story is found in Book XI &amp; XII-11</comments><date>August 1881</date><storypages>9921</storypages><category>Plants and animals</category><category>Custom and daily life</category><author>!nanni (XI)</author><keyword><kw>plant</kw><subkw>|u&apos; ||ke&apos;</subkw></keyword>
